Bonus — Flashback on Operating Systems

Hans-Martin von Gaudecker, Gregor Böhl

A bit of Operating System History

  • At special request of former students

  • Two broad sets: Unix-based/inspired (Linux, MacOS X) and Windows.

  • Unix was developed at Bell labs starting 1969 (some history), quickly evolved to become the main OS for servers.

Unix-inspired

  • Licensed to many companies for free as Bell labs (a subsidiary of AT&T) could not charge anything because of AT&T's telecommunications monopoly.
  • The monopoly was broken up in the early 1980s and Unix became a commercial product.
  • Early spin-offs: Berkeley Software Distribution (BSD) and GNU's Not Unix (GNU, only utilities, not the kernel itself).
  • In 1991, Linus Torvalds wrote a new kernel inspired by the Unix kernel from scratch — Linux.

Unix-inspired

  • Many flavours of Linux today: Debian, Ubuntu, Red Hat, Mint, Android, ...
  • After parting ways with Apple in the 1980s, Steve Jobs founded a company called NeXT.
  • Developed the OS NeXTSTEP, which was based partly on the BSD.
  • NeXT was bought by Apple in 1997, which brought back Jobs as CEO.
  • macOS X, iOS, ... all based on NeXTSTEP and thus BSD, Unix.
  • The Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX) aims to establish a standard for Unix derivatives.

Windows

  • With a couple of exceptions, completely separate from Unix world.
  • Complex history of corporate collaborations between Microsoft / IBM.
  • Big break between MS-DOS / Windows 9x and Windows NT, XP, subsequent versions.

  • The standard Windows command shell still looks like what I remember MS-DOS to look like in the early 1990s...
  • Some convergence as of late: Windows 10 includes the Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL)
